message.content: Quercus montana, commonly known as the mountain oak, is a deciduous tree species native to North America. It can grow up to 82 feet tall and has a trunk diameter of up to 3 feet. The bark of the tree is dark brown, rough and deeply furrowed. The leaves are large, glossy green in color, and can measure up to 9 inches long. The acorns are also large, measuring up to 1 inch in length, and have a distinctive cap that encloses up to 1/3 of the nut. Quercus montana is commonly found in upland forests, mountains, and rocky ridges, and is an important source of food for various wildlife species. The wood of the tree is highly valued for its strength, durability, and attractive grain, and is used in the production of furniture, flooring, and veneer.
